What You Can Now Remove
In selectSupplier() and selectSupplierForInf(), the chosen entity is used purely for reading getAttempts() to decide which supplier wins. But now the in-memory tracker owns that count, so the query sort (findByProofingLevelSorted) still works correctly for config reads ‚Äî it‚Äôs using totalAttempts to filter, which never changes. The only thing that changes is we no longer call callingOTP() which was the UPDATE. Both callingOTP() methods in the service can be kept but will simply never be called from this path anymore.

Why This Is Correct and Safe



|Concern                       |Answer                                                                                                                                                                                                             |
|------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|**Thread safety**             |`AtomicInteger` inside `ConcurrentHashMap.computeIfAbsent` ‚Äî fully thread-safe, no `synchronized` needed                                                                                                           |
|**App server restart**        |Counter resets to 0. The very next transaction reads `totalAttempts` from DB and starts the cycle fresh. Off-by-one at restart is acceptable ‚Äî Palin confirmed in the transcript: *‚Äúone or two difference is fine‚Äù*|
|**Multiple WebSphere nodes**  |Each JVM has its own tracker. This mirrors the current behavior ‚Äî the DB counter was also not truly consistent across nodes under round-robin. The tracker is no worse, and eliminates the lock entirely           |
|**Config change via Admin UI**|Admin still writes `totalAttempts` to DB as before. Next time `getByProofingLevelSorted` runs, it reads the new percentage. Call `resetAll()` optionally after an admin config change if you want instant effect   |
|**`attempts` column in DB**   |Palin‚Äôs question was answered: it‚Äôs not used anywhere else for business logic. It can remain in the DB schema untouched ‚Äî you simply stop writing to it. No schema change needed                                   |
